body:
I think the main problem here is that we were naively init `ZstdInputStreamNoFinalizer` so it would use `NoPool` underneath, which by default does not recycle the buffer pool (`release()` being a no-op).

The fix here is to use a buffer pool that would recycle the buffer for more efficient memory usage.

@jfirebaugh you could try changing the init of `ZstdInputStreamNoFinalizer` inside `ZstdDecompressingOutputStream` to make use of `RecyclingBufferPool.INSTANCE`.

```java
  public ZstdDecompressingOutputStream(OutputStream out) throws IOException {
    this.out = out;
    zis =
        new ZstdInputStreamNoFinalizer(
                new InputStream() {
                  @Override
                  public int read() {
                    return inner.read();
                  }

                  @Override
                  public int read(byte[] b, int off, int len) {
                    return inner.read(b, off, len);
                  }
                }, RecyclingBufferPool.INSTANCE)
            .setContinuous(true);
  }
```

This would probably require some careful benchmarking against your current setup to observe if the memory usage is any better.
